TEXT.English:
Verlain tried to avoid bakeries. He never bought his bread there and even went so far as to choose side streets to get around them. This time though he had had no choice. He had been hired by a wealthy corn benafactor to act as his bodyguard and when his employer chose to visit a baker here in Karinstedt, he could hardly refuse to acompany him since he had already been paid. So he stood in the vending room of the bakery and watched the baker, a small man with a friendly face and white fringes of hair, haggled with his grossly fat protectee. One other bodyguard had come with them, a young amurite mage called Leoris but he seemed bored with this duty and had wandered off to inspect the different ingriedients the bakery stocked. Verlain had no need to, he could still have named most of them by their smell alone.
His thoughts went back in time and as always when he visited a bakery he could almost hear his fathers jovial voice berating Gralf the apprentice for burning some cakes. He had never seen his father really angry. The worst mood he ever saw him in was after Verlain and Riara, his sister, had started a flour fight in the bakery. And even then there was more concern for their safety in his mean, than anger at their foolishness. The smells here were not the same, this bakery seemed to use more anis and marjery than that of his father, but they were similar enough to incite a pang of homesickness, also the smell of the cakes made him remember his mothers smile. But such thoughts were no good he knew, and he tried to keep focused on the business at hand. This was hard since in the dimly lit bakery the only thing else he could focus on were his employer and the baker haggling over the price of rice grains. And business had always bored Verlain. So he started to count the flour sacks stacked against the wall for he knew that for every fond memory he indulged in now one other would come back to him in his nightmares this night. No he would keep focused and not think about how it all ended. Thirty two sacks of flour. Seventy five loafes of bread. Two pails of water. Three big ovens. 5 pairs of footprints on the flour dusted floor. He remained calm while his left hand went to one of the flour sacks, his right hand to the pommel of his sword and his eyes followed the tracks to his masters back.
-Verlain, a mercenaries life (autobiography) {chapter one - see chapter two at the Sidar "ghost" - editor}

